I"À<p>Paul Davis‚Äô <a href="http://github.com/davisp/python-spidermonkey/tree/master"><code class="highlighter-rouge">python-spidermonkey</code></a> project looks brilliant.</p>

<p>In a nutshell, he‚Äôs building a Python bridge to Mozilla‚Äôs <a href="http://www.mozilla.org/js/spidermonkey/">SpiderMonkey</a> ‚ÄúJavaScript on C‚Äù environment.  I‚Äôm excited about that, because it means I might be able to put together a headless testing environment without trying to make everything work correctly inside Rhino.  Hooray for options!</p>

<p>I ran into a snag or two while getting up and running on JeOS (my <a href="http://intranation.com/entries/2009/03/development-virtual-machines-os-x-using-vmware-and/">dev environment of choice</a>), so I‚Äôm documenting the process here.</p>

<ol>
  <li>
    <p>Install python headers and <code class="highlighter-rouge">pkg-config</code>.  Forgetting to install
<code class="highlighter-rouge">pgk-config</code> will give you some exciting errors in the compilation phase
later on that make it sound like NSPR failed to install correctly.  If
you‚Äôre on JeOS, it‚Äôs more likely the case that you don‚Äôt have <code class="highlighter-rouge">pkg-config</code>
at all:</p>

    <div class="highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>sudo apt-get install python2.6-dev pkg-config
</code></pre></div>    </div>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Install netscape portable runtime:</p>

    <div class="highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>sudo apt-get install libnspr4-dev
</code></pre></div>    </div>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Pull down python-spidermonkey</p>

    <div class="highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>mkdir -p ~/src
cd ~/src
git clone git://github.com/davisp/python-spidermonkey.gitnsp
</code></pre></div>    </div>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Build <code class="highlighter-rouge">python-spidermonkey</code></p>

    <div class="highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>cd ~/src/python-spidermonkey
python setup.py build
</code></pre></div>    </div>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Test <code class="highlighter-rouge">python-spidermonkey</code>:</p>

    <p>Actually, <strong>don‚Äôt</strong> do this.  <a href="http://davisp.lighthouseapp.com/projects/26898-python-spidermonkey/tickets/15-test_exceed_time-fails-on-jeos">One of the tests fails on JeOS</a>, and it
fails in a way that sucks up all your resources and leaves you in an
infinite loop.  Yay!</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Install:  Even though the max time test fails (spectacularly), the bridge
seems to work pretty well.  Install the package anyway, just don‚Äôt rely on
being able to set a max execution time on your code.  :)</p>

    <div class="highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>sudo python setup.py install
</code></pre></div>    </div>
  </li>
</ol>

<p>Now, to see about getting <a href="http://jslint.com/">JSLint</a> running in this environment‚Ä¶ Fun!</p>

